":"Midlothian, Skotland, United Kingdom","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1252–about 1329":"1252–circa 1329","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1226–1296":"1226–1296","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1337":"1337","about 1329":"circa 1329","1226":"1226","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","about 1278":"circa 1278","1283":"1283","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1252–about 1329":"1252–about 1329","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1226–1296":"1226–1296","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1337":"1337","about 1329":"about 1329","1226":"1226","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","about 1278":"about 1278","1283":"1283","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Preston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one of the many places (most notably one in Lancashire) so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","occasionally from Middle English <i>prest</i> + <i>son</i> ‘son of the priest’. Priests were forbidden marriage but many produced illegitimate offspring."],"variants":[{"name":"Presson","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): variant of   Preston  .","French: occupational name for a presser of wine or oil, from a derivative of <i>presser</i> ‘to press’."]},{"name":"Prestwich","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire (now Greater Manchester), so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying settlement’, or from other places with the same derivation. Variants such as <i>Prestidge</i>, <i>Prestage</i>, etc., parallel the local pronunciation of the Lancashire name. Compare   Preston  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Preston was born in 1252, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Baron William Preston, was 26 and his mother, Sybil Ross, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Eda. He died about 1329, in Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1252–about 1329":"1252–umbes 1329","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1226–1296":"1226–1296","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1337":"1337","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1226":"1226","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","about 1278":"umbes 1278","1283":"1283","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1252–about 1329":"1252–noin 1329","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1226–1296":"1226–1296","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1337":"1337","about 1329":"noin 1329","1226":"1226","1278":"1278","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","about 1278":"noin 1278","1283":"1283","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Crichton Castle, England"